        <h3 class="title is-4">Goat Curry</h3>
        <p>Description: Experience the rich and aromatic flavors of this classic Indian dish. Tender pieces of goat meat are slow-cooked in a fragrant blend of spices, tomatoes, and yogurt, creating a hearty and comforting curry that's perfect with steamed rice or naan bread.</p>

        <div class="recipe-details" style="max-height: 300px; overflow-y: auto;">
          <h4 class="subtitle is-5">Ingredients</h4>
          <ul>
            <li>1 kg goat meat, cut into chunks</li>
            <li>2 large onions, finely chopped</li>
            <li>4 tomatoes, pureed</li>
            <li>1/2 cup plain yogurt</li>
            <li>4 cloves garlic, minced</li>
            <li>1-inch piece of ginger, grated</li>
            <li>2 tablespoons vegetable oil</li>
            <li>2 teaspoons cumin powder</li>
            <li>2 teaspoons coriander powder</li>
            <li>1 teaspoon turmeric powder</li>
            <li>1 teaspoon chili powder (adjust to taste)</li>
            <li>Salt to taste</li>
            <li>Fresh coriander leaves for garnish</li>
          </ul>

          <h4 class="subtitle is-5">Preparation</h4>
          <ol>
            <li>Heat oil in a large pot or pressure cooker. Add chopped onions and sauté until golden brown.</li>
            <li>Add minced garlic and grated ginger. Sauté for another minute.</li>
            <li>Add cumin powder, coriander powder, turmeric powder, and chili powder. Stir well.</li>
            <li>Add tomato puree and cook until the oil starts to separate from the masala.</li>
            <li>Add goat meat and cook for a few minutes until it changes color.</li>
            <li>Stir in yogurt and salt. Mix well.</li>
            <li>If using a pressure cooker, cover and cook for about 4-5 whistles or until the meat is tender. If using a regular pot, cover and simmer on low heat until meat is tender (about 2-3 hours).</li>
            <li>Garnish with fresh coriander leaves and serve hot with steamed rice or naan bread.</li>
          </ol>
        </div>

